04603nam a22008295i 9780814790915DE-B159720220329044247.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220329t20042004nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808147909157 a10.18574/nyu/97808147909152doi  a(DE-B1597)547779  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aRM332 7aPSY0000002bisacsh04a616.85/270612221 aHealy, David, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aLet Them Eat Prozac :bThe Unhealthy Relationship Between the Pharmaceutical Industry and Depression /cDavid Healy. 1aNew York, NY : bNew York University Press, c[2004] 4c©2004  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tPreface: Under the Thundercloud of a Common Experience -- tIntroduction: Before Prozac -- t1 Take One -- t2 Events in Kentucky -- t3 Down the Barrel of a Lawyer -- t4 Market Force -- t5 A Pacific Fault Line -- t6 Kafka's Castle -- t7 Experiment at the End of the Millennium -- t8 The Plots Thicken -- t9 The Tort Wars -- t10 Let Them Eat Prozac -- tEpilogue: Anecdotal Deaths -- tNotes -- tIndex -- tAbout the Author0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aProzac. Paxil. Zoloft. Turn on your television and you are likely to see a commercial for one of the many selective serotonin reuptake inhibitors (SSRIs) on the market. We hear a lot about them, but do we really understand how these drugs work and what risks are involved for anyone who uses them?Let Them Eat Prozac explores the history of SSRIs-from their early development to their latest marketing campaigns-and the controversies that surround them. Initially, they seemed like wonder drugs for those with mild to moderate depression. When Prozac was released in the late 1980s, David Healy was among the psychiatrists who prescribed it. But he soon observed that some of these patients became agitated and even attempted suicide. Could the new wonder drug actually be making patients worse?Healy draws on his own research and expertise to demonstrate the potential hazards associated with these drugs. He intersperses case histories with insider accounts of the research leading to the development and approval of SSRIs as a treatment for depression. Let Them Eat Prozac clearly demonstrates that the problems go much deeper than a side-effect of a particular drug. The pharmaceutical industry would like us to believe that SSRIs can safely treat depression, anxiety, and a host of other mental problems. But, as Let Them Eat Prozac reveals, this “cure” may be worse than the disease.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mrz 2022) 0aDepression, MentalxChemotherapy. 0aFluoxetine. 0aPsychotropic drugs industry. 0aSerotonin uptake inhibitors. 7aPSYCHOLOGY / General.2bisacsh  aExploring.  aSSRIs-.  acampaigns-.  acontroversies.  adevelopment.  aearly.  afrom.  ahistory.  alatest.  amarketing.  asurround.  athat.  atheir.  athem.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070644440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814790915423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780814790915/original  a978-3-11-070644-4  New York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MDPM  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MDPM  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK